AGI - Israel prepares to attack Rafah and en masse tanks along the southern border with Gaza, to the Israeli pass of Kerem Shalom. Egypt tries to mediate the last hour to try to block the offensive and sends a delegation to Israel to resume talks for a temporary ceasefire between Israel and Hamas and the release of hostages. The team is led by Abbas Kamel, the powerful leader of the Egyptian intelligence who should meet the head of the Mossad David Barnea and the national security advisor Tzachi Hanegbi.
&nbsp;
The current proposal for an agreement between Israel and Hamas provides for the release of 33 hostages, including women, soldiers, adults and wounded. The duration of the ceasefire within the agreement will depend on the number of kidnapped released. According to a Saudi source, Egypt would nevertheless submit a new proposal to Israel to freeze the operation to Rafah in exchange for the start of negotiations.
&nbsp;
In the border city, shelter for over a million Palestinians, the international community and humanitarian organizations fear a bloodbath. According to Israeli sources Netanyahu would not have given the ok to the operation yet, but it all makes us think it is imminent. In the meantime the great escape has begun. According to the Idf, about 150,000 to 200,000 Palestinian civilians have already left Rafah on 7 April. And it's between 80,000 and 100,000 who came to Egypt.
&nbsp;
Cairo will then try everything to avoid the worst. According to the Israeli website Walla, which mentions a high Israeli official, discussions concern a proposal for the initial release of 20 hostages considered "humanitarian" cases. A political leader of Hamas, Ghazi Hamad, has assured Afp from Qatar that an assault on Rafah will not allow Israel to get "what he wants", i.e. to "eliminate Hamas or recover" the hostages. But Netanyahu continues to believe that an offensive is necessary to defeat Hamas and free the hostages. A complex situation that will see Tuesday also the descent into the field of the American secretary Antony Blinken, on his seventh trip to Israel from October 7.
&nbsp;
Meanwhile, the Tel Aviv army announced today that an Israeli civilian was killed during the night near the border by missiles launched from southern Lebanon, where they destroyed the Hezbollah infrastructure. "In the night, the terrorists launched anti-tank missiles in the Har Dov area, in northern Israel, an Israeli civilian who worked on an infrastructure project was wounded and subsequently declared dead," reads in the Army statement.&nbsp;

