<h2>Hamas will lay down weapons for an independent Palestinian State
Khalil al-Hayya, one of Hamas' leading political wing leaders, said that the Islamist group is ready to accept a truce with five-year-old Israel or even more, and that it will depose weapons if an independent Palestinian state will be created along the borders prior to 1967. In an interview with the Associated Press in Istanbul, al-Hayya - which is considered the vice of Yahya Sinwar, the head of Hamas in Gaza, and who participates in the negotiations with Israel - said that the Palestinian terrorist group would be willing to dissolve the Egyptian Al-Qassam Brigades "if a fully sovereign Palestinian state was established in the West Bank and in the Gaza Strip". It is a change of position compared to the Hamas founding paper that wants the destruction of Israel and that states that the Palestinian people must enjoy the entire land "which extends from the Jordan River to the East to the Mediterranean to the west", echoing the famous anti-Israeli slogan "from the river to the sea, Palestine will be free".
